WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.360
Hi everyone, my name is Therese Anders and I'm a postdoctoral research fellow at the

00:00:12.360 --> 00:00:14.000
Hertie School in Berlin.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.500
And today I will talk to you about how to conduct peer review in data science classes

00:00:18.500 --> 00:00:23.040
using the GH class package.

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:24.680
So why does peer review matter?

00:00:24.680 --> 00:00:29.400
Well, it's a great active learning tool for students and in particular for instructors

00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:34.279
in really large data science classes, peer review enables them to provide their students

00:00:34.279 --> 00:00:39.200
with meaningful, substantive feedback beyond what might be possible with kind of standard

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:44.160
automated code review tools.

00:00:44.160 --> 00:00:49.279
The GH class package now offers software solutions to do this in R and this is work that I did

00:00:49.279 --> 00:00:53.840
during my internship with RStudio this past summer together with Meena Chettinkaya-Rundell

00:00:53.840 --> 00:00:55.480
and Colin Rundell.

00:00:55.480 --> 00:01:00.720
And so in a nutshell, GH class is a package that allows you to manage a class that is

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:07.220
run as a GitHub organization via R commands interfacing with the GitHub API.

00:01:07.220 --> 00:01:13.959
And as a new feature, we now added the ability to also conduct peer review with this structure.

00:01:13.959 --> 00:01:17.760
So what are some of the key features that GH class allows you to do?

00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:24.239
Well, first and foremost, GH class will allow you to automate the process of distributing

00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:29.720
and subsequently collecting all the reviews on GitHub repositories.

00:01:29.720 --> 00:01:35.480
The package will allow you to create a randomized review roster for your class and you can also

00:01:35.480 --> 00:01:40.440
assign more than one reviewer to an assignment.

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:45.059
The package allows you to automatically collect the scores that students gave to each other.

00:01:45.059 --> 00:01:49.599
You as the instructor can determine whether you want the review to be single or double

00:01:49.599 --> 00:01:50.839
blind.

00:01:50.839 --> 00:01:55.120
And last but certainly not least, this works for a number of different assignments.

00:01:55.120 --> 00:02:01.599
So this could work for a very small coding homework or even an entire final project.

00:02:01.599 --> 00:02:03.199
Okay.

00:02:03.199 --> 00:02:07.639
So let me briefly demo for you the four main steps that you need to know in order to do

00:02:07.639 --> 00:02:09.320
this with GH class.

00:02:09.320 --> 00:02:14.919
So suppose we have three students in our class and they submitted their homework one homework

00:02:14.919 --> 00:02:17.279
via GitHub repositories.

00:02:17.279 --> 00:02:23.000
We can initiate the peer review process by creating so-called review repositories for

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:29.399
each of these students and the peer init function will automatically do this for you.

00:02:29.399 --> 00:02:32.759
The second step is to actually assign the review.

00:02:32.759 --> 00:02:36.839
And so in my little graphic on my slides, I'm going to be focusing on the example of

00:02:36.839 --> 00:02:43.240
Bruno as the assignment author in red and Anya as the randomly assigned reviewer for

00:02:43.240 --> 00:02:45.300
this assignment in blue.

00:02:45.300 --> 00:02:50.619
So what peer assign does, it takes Bruno's assignment, makes a copy of it, and stores

00:02:50.619 --> 00:02:54.380
it in a separate folder on Anya's review repository.

00:02:54.380 --> 00:02:58.619
And this folder is anonymized, so Anya doesn't know whose assignment she's reviewing.

00:02:58.619 --> 00:03:04.419
And what peer assign also does is it adds a R markdown feedback form to this repository

00:03:04.419 --> 00:03:06.779
that we're going to ask Anya to fill out.

00:03:06.779 --> 00:03:07.779
Okay.

00:03:07.779 --> 00:03:11.539
So here we're going to do a little bit of time traveling here.

00:03:11.539 --> 00:03:17.139
Because this is the part in the review process where our students would actually conduct

00:03:17.139 --> 00:03:19.339
the review.

00:03:19.339 --> 00:03:24.619
And so what our students are going to do is they're going to edit the original assignment

00:03:24.619 --> 00:03:30.259
of the authors and also fill out the review form that we asked them to do.

00:03:30.259 --> 00:03:35.020
Once this process is done, you as the instructor can now collect the scores that the students

00:03:35.020 --> 00:03:36.460
gave to each other.

00:03:36.460 --> 00:03:42.419
And so the peer score review form will essentially extract the scores from the R markdown file

00:03:42.419 --> 00:03:48.139
of the reviewers and store the information in either a data frame or a CSV file.

00:03:48.139 --> 00:03:49.139
All right.

00:03:49.139 --> 00:03:50.899
We are already at step four.

00:03:50.899 --> 00:03:56.139
So the last step in this review process is to take all the review files from the reviewers

00:03:56.139 --> 00:03:58.419
and move it all back to the authors.

00:03:58.419 --> 00:04:01.139
And so this is what peer return will do for you.

00:04:01.139 --> 00:04:06.979
So it will essentially clone the author one folder from Anya's review repository and make

00:04:06.979 --> 00:04:10.940
a copy of it on Bruno's original assignment repository.

00:04:10.940 --> 00:04:15.539
And so now Bruno could go and actually take a look at the feedback that he got.

00:04:15.539 --> 00:04:18.140
What does this look like from the student's perspective?

00:04:18.140 --> 00:04:24.459
Well, peer return will also automatically open an issue on Bruno's GitHub repository

00:04:24.459 --> 00:04:28.980
that gives him some instructions of what to do and also has links to all the great feedback

00:04:28.980 --> 00:04:30.500
that Anya gave him.

00:04:30.500 --> 00:04:35.500
And so, for example, if he was to click on this assignment.RMD file, what happens is

00:04:35.500 --> 00:04:40.779
he would automatically be seeing a GitHub diff between his original assignment and then

00:04:40.779 --> 00:04:43.059
all the feedback that Anya gave him.

00:04:43.059 --> 00:04:44.059
All right.

00:04:44.059 --> 00:04:45.059
There you go.

00:04:45.059 --> 00:04:49.140
You learned how to conduct peer review with the GH class package.

00:04:49.140 --> 00:04:54.100
And we have a package down site available if you want to know more where we have a ton

00:04:54.100 --> 00:04:58.820
of really great vignettes, step-by-step guides, and also instructions that you can pass on

00:04:58.820 --> 00:04:59.820
to your students.

00:05:00.140 --> 00:05:01.140
Thank you very much.

00:05:01.140 --> 00:05:02.140
Thank you.

00:05:02.140 --> 00:05:03.140
Thank you.

00:05:03.140 --> 00:05:04.140
Thank you.

00:05:04.140 --> 00:05:04.140


